description.narrative:
The results have mainly been achieved and include outputs as a proposal for a long-term capacity building project and four technical studies that informed the project proposal. 
The technical studies conducted are:
1. Capacity needs assessment and Capacity development plan;
2. ENR sector policy and research gaps analysis and a list of priorities of analytical studies;
3. ENR sector gender assessment, Gender budget statement and Gender mainstreaming strategy and its implementation plan;
4. ENR sector staff retention policy and its implementation strategy. 
The Capacity needs assessment covered the Ministry, affiliated Agencies, Civil Society and the private sector was successfully carried out. The findings on Capacity Gaps were presented at Institutional, Organizational and Individual Levels and captured according to the ENR sub-sectors which are (i) Environmental Management; (ii)   Integrated Water Resources Management; (iii) Forest Resources Management; (iv) Land Management and Use; (v) Mining, Petroleum and Gas and (vi) Meteorological Services.
At each level (Institutional, Organizational and Individual Levels) capacity challenges in comparison with required capacity were acknowledged as well as required capacity building actions from which a capacity development plan to bridge the identified gaps was developed. 
The review of existing Policies and Research gaps highlighted a list of priorities that will allow the Ministry to know the areas which need policy reviews and research topics that can be prioritized. Study also revealed that existing policies have some discrepancies with the Green Growth and Climate Resilient Strategy and identified priority researches to be carried out in five key subsectors (land use and management; forestry and nature conservation; Environment, climate change and meteorological services; integrated water resources management; mining and quarries sector). The Terms of reference for these studies were also developed.
The Gender Analysis generated data on which the Ministry based indicators that will guide the planning processes to ensure gender is mainstreamed across Environment and Natural Resources Sector. Gender budget statement guidelines were also developed and approved. Study on Gender gaps analysis covered key policies from the ENR sub-sectors, namely: Forestry, Water, Land, Meteorology, Mining and Climate change. In addition, Gender gaps was assessed in the perspective of Institutional arrangement and implementation procedures and the analysis highlighted key areas to consider for Gender mainstreaming strategy to ensure Gender equality and equity is promoted across ENR Sector.
Retention strategy: A study based on gap analysis of the problems in connection with staff retention in the ENR sector was conducted and suggested ways to deal with the situation  highlighting seven Strategic Objectives.
In addition to the outputs mentioned above the project has supported Capacity development of existing Green Growth and Climate Resilience Strategy (GGCRS) Focal Persons. This has been done through giving them the opportunity to work in selected Sectors and Districts to test methods and develop best practice. The Focal Persons in selected Districts and Sub-sectors has proven the importance of a monitoring framework to ensure focused implementation of the GGCRS. This team has been supporting the Environmental and Natural Resources (ENR) Sector in mainstreaming Sector indicators in their institutions. Technically, nominated Focal points played a role from Planning phase by ensuring key performance indicators of the GGCRS are integrated in their Action and Strategic Plans.This resulted in Institutions’ ownership and accountability with regards to their contribution in GGCRS implementation.
For example this has included activities such as:
1. Support in carrying out various Baseline assessments including study on building resilience of communities living in degraded forests, savannah and wetlands of Rwanda through Ecosystem based adaptation approach; 
2. Support in developing the Green Building Minimum Guidelines;
3. Intervene in District Planning and Budgeting to ensure integration of Agro forestry, forest targets in District planning cycle;
MoE is of the opinion that there is a need to establish a network of Focal Persons in all Districts and Sub Sectors of ENR Sector to ensure full ownership, thus enhancing significant contribution to the ENR Sector performance by all Districts and Sub-sectors.
